<font color="#FF0000">NOT BLUE</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jun 27 23:26:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tao Guo,<br><br>
I appreciate your words of gratitude.<br><br>
We are back in Vietnam today and the optimist in me feels that there is still potential for us to be &quot;liberators&quot; - at least in the sense that we will help rebuild Vietnam. I truly hope that the country will become prosperous and peaceful. The potential for great achievement is there.<br><br>
The situation there and in Hong Kong bear watching. We live in an ever changing world, right?<br><br>
As for &quot;the other side&quot; in Vietnam, I am sure that they have their share of disillusionment. Once the communists took over, it was up to them to live up to their promises. How much of their failure is a result of presiding over a country that was devastated by war? Possibly foreign investment will create success? Rather than looking at &quot;success&quot; as a useful tool for the communists, I much rather view any good things that result from our latest presence in Vietnam as being good things that will benefit the people. So it is better to be hopeful than blue.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


